text: @tingmichael @adrianscottcom @eldsjal @Spotify @stewart @SlackHQ That system was separate from the broader network. What most people don't know about DL -- its done right on the exact same systems used in the market every day. Allocation blind and programmatic.

Our entire industry benefits from the work of these pioneers; we owe them all our gratitude. Michael Moritz said "the choice of a direct listing or a traditional IPO has become a test of two attributes: courage and intelligence." The "courage" part is the hardest of the two. 🙏

text: Kudos to @dougjoe & the team at @GoodRx. Doug has paid his dues w/ stints at big companies and many, many years with his "nose to the startup grindstone." These success stories of years & years of hard work are a nice contrast to the many 19 year-old drop-outs. Well deserved.

Why would anyone choose to be anti-innovation? They might not know that they are. They are merely trying to protect old hierarchies, maintain the status quo, or keep an industry as it was in the past. However, this Ludicious protectionism has very real long-term consequences.

Governments (around globe & across time) either play a supporting role in encouraging innovation or destructive role in discouraging it. Europe is lagging in such support. The U.S. has been a leader but is showing signs of calcification. China is clearly in the driver's seat.

He recognizes how critical innovation is to our world. It is central to such things as solving poverty, curing disease/health, & raising the welfare/standard of living for most humans. Most problems created by the scaling of our globe need innovations as the key solution.

Relative to our world in Silicon Valley, Matt shows how "what we do" is not new, but a very old (and critically important) process. He refers to idea generation as "invention," & notes that successful "go to market" (which he calls innovation) is far more important. Agree 10x!

text: One of the most amazing things about both books is Matt's ability to connect the dots across very long time horizons. Very few can. He also has the ability to combine thinking from many fields - most notably science, technology, psychology, & a heavy dose of microeconomics.

text: One company I worked with went to do a secondary 4 months after IPO, and only 10% of the IPO shares were still held. It's ludicrous to think you can "control" who owns your stock. IPO allocators aren't locked up, and once your public, your investors choose you. And that's OK.

Two other thoughts. One of the main arguments for hand-allocation is "you want to choose long term shareholders." $SNOW sold 32.2mm shares last night. Today, 35.7mm shares traded; how does that work? And no one checks to see who held, who sold, etc. Never measured/disclosed.

In many ways, $SNOW is the final proof of just how broken process is. Frank Slootman is a HIGHLY experienced IPO CEO. He knows the game, & pushed hard to make sure he wasn't short-changing the company. But it didn't matter, because the process is set up to deliver this silliness.

text: @akramsrazor @EghosaO If you gave away $400mm it is 800x more expensive than a super bowl ad.

This "order-matching" is used universally with other financial assets, & is the EXACT process used in a direct listing - same algo, people, computers. EXACT same systems. The DL just skips the part where the humans make massive errors that cost hundred of millions of dollars.

The next morning after an IPO allocation, a market maker (computer in Nasdaq) aggregates supply/demand and does a blind "match" to determine market open price. This is smart, rational, intelligent. This is how you find the "market" price. See "price-time": https://t.co/SDAPIzjZLq

Another way of saying this (see below) is the human bankers chose a price that was 30% of what the market eventually decided. This is unfathomable levels of being wrong. Why allow humans to chose prices when we can just match supply and demand? (next thread) https://t.co/L4Z8us1HyV

No market dynamic on demand side whatsoever. If you go through a broken-IPO you will see this. "So and so" client "has to be in." You definitely want "client B" on your cap chart. No one should make 7% selling stock at a massive discount to buyers the company already knew.

Some may wonder how the broken IPO process is getting worse. Simply supply/demand. The UWs are focusing on fewer and fewer accounts as potential buyers (while ignoring more and more demand). A handful of their (the UWs) best clients (10-15) are negotiating the price "they" want.

@seandougfan You can argue that, but "we" can't because I don't agree with it. Stock finds its true owners faster with DL. @TheRealCarlChi1 can share with you the details.

I am really surprised we haven't seen a derivative suit with one of these underpriced IPOs brought on behalf of ex-employees. Failure to use market-based pricing approach is arguably malfeasance, as is giving away $400mm+ in a single day. Simply poor corporate governance.

If your company is considering going public, & you don't want to "give-away" your hard earned equity capital to fund a 1-day "pop" wealth-transfer, tell your CEO/CFO/GC to use a modern approach with (A) market-pricing, & (B) open access. The DL does both. IPO has neither.

With these 4 IPOs ($VRM, $ZI, $WMG, $FOUR), the average underpricing cost $483mm per company. For most SV companies, employees own 25% of the company. Underpricing this way robs your own employees of $120mm. This choice of Direct Listing vs IPO matters for all employees.

text: One of my favorite writers/thinkers on healthcare hit a home run with this post. It is truly a "must read" Covid piece. "Treat the Patient, Not the Virus" by @david_goldhill  https://t.co/FJ1PXEIVby

SIPing has massive costs as well. Not just the immediate economic harm to the families that can afford it least, but  long-term physical health & mental health issues caused by the pain of the economic ruin. There are no easy answers here. Consequences in all directions.

If you argue we need to keep SIPing, even though hospitals are not overwhelmed, the question then would be "to what end?" Most smart experts  say a vaccine could be 9-18 months away. Do you recommend SIP for that entire time? What is the goal in that case? And who owns that harm?

text: Remember that SIP (Shelter in Place) was a "tactic" to prevent overwhelming the hospitals. It was never a solve for the pandemic. Never was, and cannot be. Today in U.S., most hospitals are not overwhelmed, so it would be natural to assume that we would start to open up.

Crazy time in what we hope is a once in a lifetime event. Some people are mad/angry about NOT opening up. And others are angry about those that want to open up and are not shy about using strong language to defend their position. Politics amplifies the rhetoric and the emotion.
@gavindebt @MalteLandwehr @alice__LG As @sapinker and @mattwridley would tell you, predicting apocalyptic events has been a common activity over the history of the world.

text: Am I cavalier about Zoom's security? No. 4 thoughts. 1) The primary issue was caused by users not using a PW that is already in the product. 2) I have met @ericsyuan who is both gracious & sincere. He is on it, & I believe him. https://t.co/Dkz1FyrzSs

The products of the forerunners/precursors to Zoom were "non-optimal." There were difficult to install, it was hard to initiate a meeting, & they were less intuitive. I have been surprised at how many people I know in all walks of life who have taken to the product so naturally.

In his recent podcast with @patrick_oshag, @GavinSBaker talks about Zoom (27:35). He notes that "very small differences in UI/UX matter immensely." And as a result, Zoom is now "woven into the fabric of our society." Worth a listen. https://t.co/QUYedAhRL6

We talk a lot in Silicon Valley about "first-mover advantage." But Zoom was hardly a first-mover. The biggest & brightest companies have coveted this space for years & invested against it. Cisco, Microsoft, Google, Facebook. But Zoom was the one that broke out.

At least you know who to blame - the cavalier proselytizers of the SPL religion.

Some will try to "go public at the last minute" as a last resort. Multiples are contracting, odds of getting out now much lower. This desperate act is like running to your gate, even thought you know you are 30 minutes late, & watching helplessly as the plane taxis away.

Now add  Corona Virus & a negative macro event (we had one in 2001 & 2009, could have been assumed there would be another), & the game is even trickier. This could push your IPO "window" many years into the future; you need healthy market & to recover from hit to your financials.

Massive "myth" that you have to be really big to IPO. People say things like "you need $100mm in revenue." I worked on three companies that IPOed after a $10mm/quarter. People want to wait until things are  "predictable." But getting bigger makes 25% growth harder, not easier. https://t.co/CrZ5d8c2aY

As you can tell, I am fascinated with the notion of far analogies & thrilled that @DavidEpstein did so much work in highlighting why this interdisciplinary/cross functional thinking leads to so much creative output. Please pick it up. Lateral learning will lead to breakthroughs.

text: This type of interdisciplinary research is the founding principle of the Santa Fe Institute @sfiscience, where @mjmauboussin, @wolfejosh, I are fortunate enough to spend time. To learn more, I highly recommend Complexity by Waldrop (my personal fav book). https://t.co/Z1ySFSb4pd
Companies that move people between different function groups are also practicing this art. Another is to use competitive cross-functional teams at off-sites as a way to generate out-of-the-box ideas.

Many companies promote a speaker series. This is a great way to see multiple far analogies. Make sure to bring in CEOs that are successful in different areas, but drill down into the key insights that led to their success.  What can be applied in your work?

I have often wondered if lateral learning could be expressly encouraged. E.g., as a founder/CEO ask each executive to generate new relationships with similar functional execs at companies in different industries to look for areas of learning. Have them all report back 2/year.

Range highlights that many breakthrough innovations happen when someone from a far away field (where they may have deep knowledge) brings new thinking & approaches to a new field of study. This "lateral" learning is quite different from "expert" learning, which is also important.

Over the years, I searched for more work on this concept, but never found them. Until one day @mjmauboussin (who knew I was looking) said, "you know there is a bunch of far analogy stuff in Range." There sure is. And even a reference to Keith Holyoak.

I had never heard the term "far analogies" before, but found it immediately compelling. KH argued that the best & the brightest were able to borrow ideas from fields that were further away from their own craft. He even argued this might be a tier of intelligence, & gave examples.

text: @lisahellebo This is more corporate dollars.

But this desire didn't result in more due diligence, it actually resulted in less. They probably felt like they would miss out if they asked too many questions, or they simply assumed that the other reputable players around the table already did the work. "Proxy DD".

Even though the "ask" was way above average, these "executives" approached the situation with blind optimism rather than normal investor skepticism (many have viewed this as a promote all along). & the fact that other high profile names were involved made them want it more.

There are some super interesting lessons here. My favorite is a combination of FOMO & what I call "proxy due diligence." Many famous people, companies, and investment banks were all promoted this opportunity, & a surprisingly large number of them jumped at the opportunity. https://t.co/Xah7PpOyh5

text: Talk to your lead VC if you have not received an invitation, and they can help make sure you obtain access.  https://t.co/RLkB4VXeJX

If your VC-backed company is considering an alternative to this one-sided process that takes advantage of Silicon Valley based companies, I would urge you to attend an industry-led SF-based event on Oct 1st where will explain how this happens & discuss the better alternative.

This is the reason Barry McCarthy calls the traditional IPO process "moronic" https://t.co/xwwfMsywuw Luckily he helped push for a better process. With Direct Listings, supply & demand are explicitly matched (1X subscribed). And fairness and access are assured. No orders ignored.

But the banks with the strongest brands actually provide the worst corporate execution. The top two firms (by IPO count) have underpriced on average by around 30% for the entire past 10 years over 100 IPOs each. The top 3 banks accounted for 81.3% of all underpricing. https://t.co/ehgqXoysUB

Because of this 39% "pop" the true cost of capital for this IPO is the fee (likely 5-6%) plus the mis-pricing discount. So in this case 45% - which is insane. This underpricing is now systematic. Over past 10-years the average VC-backed IPO is underpriced by 21.1% (Jay Ritter)

If you look at where that ownership would have resided were supply and demand matched, you see that this process cost investors $175mm & founders $69mm. Unfortunately, it also cost employees who would have $49mm more of the company were it not underpriced. https://t.co/qkWRGwe3Zy

text: A forced move into professionalism could be uneconomic for all but the very largest schools, & may be unconscionable for many others. This key step may cause some schools to do away with athletics altogether (which is perhaps what some of the outspoken want).

The number of NCAA athletes that would attract endorsement deals is a fraction of the 500,000 student-athletes in the NCAA. Well less than 1%. Crossing into paying certain athletes, could have secondary or tertiary order effects on the 99% that are unforeseeable at this time.

No one I know is concerned about the exploitation of NCAA tennis, golf, or baseball athletes. Why? Because those kids all have a choice to go pro without entering the college system. If both the NBA/NFL set their age to 18, these football/basketball players would have choice too.

text: One last positive thought on this. As we move through time, improvements in technology & connectivity increase transparency. When transparency increases, imperfect processes are exposed, corrected, and improved. It is simply progress. That is exactly what is happening here.

Just today, there were not one, but two $100MM+ "Silicon Valley Give-Away's" as a result of under-priced, hand-allocated IPOs. Luckily, there is now a better way (https://t.co/Ix4dDjYytm), and Silicon Valley can hopefully stop being the "patsy." https://t.co/4WBGoFIRc9

text: This is "regulatory capture" in a nutshell. It's worth reading the Wikipedia entry if you are not familiar with the concept. https://t.co/jy8yX8vO4y I have always phrased it this way "regulation is the friend of the incumbent."

They show that in each of the previous cases, regulated companies ended up outperforming the market as a result of these issues. They then recommend you BUY the stocks of any of large tech companies that trade off on weaknesses as a result of concern about future regulation.
"Fourth, attempts to regulate or even punish technology firms with dominant market position, especially those with so-called network effects, have typically backfired."

"Third, while big firms do not usually increase market share after regulatory actions, the absence of new players provides an ability to raise prices later that ultimately contributes to margin expansion."

"First, government actions aimed at increasing competition always have unintended consequences. Second, legal actions that increase the cost of compliance can also serve as a constraint on new entrants and smaller companies, thereby allowing incumbents to maintain market share."

The authors study in detail 5 different cases of previous US regulatory intervention. "A striking pattern emerges. Regulatory actions aimed at promoting competition actually had a series of tertiary repercussions that ultimately helped the existing entrenched players."

text: In many ways, the "direct listing" is just a modified form of the auction model used by Google and Netsuite. We really should move away from the archaic and nepotistic process used in a traditional IPO, and embrace a modern algorithmic approach. It's pretty straightforward.

As we sit here in 2019, it makes absolutely NO sense that a new security should be priced "by hand" or "by relationship" vs "by matching algorithm." Almost all other financial products are priced this way, & as the NYSE head said this am, this is how you start trading a spinout.

With a traditional IPO, allocation is determined based on personal relationships, your firms brand, how well you know the banker, etc. Believe it or not, with a traditional IPO, a willingness to bid the highest price WILL NOT assure you allocation in the IPO.

@AntoineGara There is a consistent perspective that a "pop" is success, and a "non-pop" (which is spectacular pricing execution) is a failure. That is quite pervasive I think you must admit.

Excited to witness another successful direct listing in the coming weeks. $WORK There is no reason whatsoever equities cannot be priced in a blind auction. Bonds have been priced/sold this way for decades. This is how 100% of IPOs should be done. And hopefully will one day.

Imagine if a CFO/CEO gave away a half a billion dollars? Or simply squandered it. How would that be viewed? This is similar, but it's institutionalized, and therefore everyone is numb to it. And the press views a "pop" as success, which is just poor financial comprehension.

text: @loganbartlett @semil No -- I think this is still a marketplace. As is Amazon's third party services.
@semil I understand the benefit of taking on more of the responsibility -- but it has a limit where you crossover into just being a market entrant. And some people are confusing the two.

In the extreme case where you employ 100% of the workers/suppliers as your own employees, at that point you actually fail to be a marketplace. You are just an agency or service provider. You have entered the industry as a normal participant. Which is fine, but not a marketplace.

Would someone be kind enough to articulate for me the key differences between a "managed marketplace" and a "true marketplace?" I am not joking, I am confused by the term which seems a bit oxymoronish to me.

text: Penny-wise and pound-foolish for everyone involved. If you are VC backed & doing any revenue whatsoever, you should get the audit. And for the late-stage investor that doesn't ask, caveat emptor. It's hard to blame anyone else when you are internally donning blinders.

Or consider – @discordap, @Nextdoor, and @marcopoloapp, three separate breakout social networks – all started in a day and age where the common wisdom is the space has "matured" and is “over.”

text: 3/ Most of the experts in the field know about this reality - one of the few times you can turn a cost item into a profit item. Historically, when a situation like this exists, someone will find a way to bring it down market, such that smaller players receive the same benefit.

2/ When you get larger it turns out, you can get "paid" to distribute $$ to suppliers. How? Well you pay them on to a debit/CC account, and when they later use that account, your partner generates interchange fees which can now be shared with you (the marketplace provider).

1/ When you are building a multi-sided network, many marketplaces need to distribute $$ to suppliers. In this past this has cost $$/transaction. Not as much as a credit card transaction, but let's say in the 50-100 bps range.

Totally agree with this point. I wish I had highlighted it in my original thread: https://t.co/Zr0Ft9iPfu
Other books that all entrepreneurs should read: 1) @MichaelEPorter, Competitive Strategy, 2) @geoffreyamoore Crossing the Chasm, 3) @claychristensen Innovator's Dilemma, and 4) @Jerry_Kaplan Startup

Another fascinating theme is how super successful and accomplished people become so personally enamored with the company's narrative being true that they shut their eyes and ears -- creating structural anti-governance.

There is a lesson in the book for every constituent -- employees, executives, investors, board members, and even corporate partners. Interestingly the employees had the most to say, but had the least amount of power - which kept them squelched.
Bad Blood by @JohnCarreyrou is an incredible book that should be read by each and every player in the startup/Silicon Valley ecosystem. https://t.co/W5ck7XBUp9
